{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17522843","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17522843"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:48:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:48:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13850"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13850","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13850"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.11,0.04,0.49,0.19]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6467"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102711"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6467","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6467"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13850"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85194"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"559"},{"type":"tags","id":"809"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12799"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16852"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16853"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23129"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33716"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36016"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102711","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102711"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a \u0027bent\u0027 finger. Several weeks ago he injured his finger whilst playing a ball game with his grandson. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The deformity is shown (\u003Ca class=\u0022vdd-added\u0022 href=\u0022https://emedici.com/storage/media/W3eVxSVU81jCHIEvF48yCTV5q9zZK9.jpg\u0022\u003EImage 1\u003C/a\u003E).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely explanation for this deformity?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Disruption of the extensor mechanism at the proximal interphalangeal (PIP) joint","Rupture of the central slip of the extensor tendon","Rupture of the flexor tendon at the metacarpophalangeal joint","Disruption of the extensor tendon at its distal insertion","Rupture of the flexor tendon at the proximal interphalangeal joint"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a swan neck deformity of his finger, characterised by fixed hyperextension of the proximal interphalangeal (PIP) joint and flexion of the distal interphalangeal (DIP) joint. In this case, the most likely cause is \u003Cstrong\u003Edisruption of the extensor tendon at its distal insertion\u003C/strong\u003E. This injury, often referred to as a mallet injury, initially causes the DIP joint to flex due to loss of terminal extensor function. Over time, the imbalance in tendon forces leads to hyperextension at the PIP joint, resulting in the characteristic swan neck deformity. This is a classic post-traumatic mechanism, especially following a forced flexion injury to the fingertip.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESwan neck deformity can result from trauma, as in this case, or from chronic inflammatory conditions such as rheumatoid arthritis. Management depends on the underlying cause and chronicity, and may include splinting, physiotherapy, or surgical intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Edisruption of the extensor mechanism at the proximal interphalangeal (PIP) joint\u003C/strong\u003E is also known as a central slip injury. This is a relatively common injury and can lead to a boutonniere deformity. This deformity involves flexion of the PIP joint and hyperextension of the distal interphalangeal (DIP) joint.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERupture of the central slip of the extensor tendon\u003C/strong\u003E typically results in a boutonniere deformity, which is characterised by flexion at the PIP joint and hyperextension at the DIP joint\u2014the opposite pattern to a swan neck deformity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERupture of the flexor tendon at the metacarpophalangeal joint\u003C/strong\u003E would primarily affect finger flexion at the metacarpophalangeal joint and would not produce the hyperextension of the PIP joint seen in a swan neck deformity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERupture of the flexor tendon at the proximal interphalangeal joint\u003C/strong\u003E would also primarily affect finger flexion, not causing the characteristic swan neck appearance.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Swan neck deformity is characterised by hyperextension of the proximal interphalangeal (PIP) joint and flexion of the distal interphalangeal (DIP) joint.","Traumatic disruption of the extensor tendon at its distal insertion can cause swan neck deformity.","Swan neck deformity can result from injury or other conditions, such as rheumatoid arthritis."],"references":["Elzinga K, Chung KC. Managing Swan Neck and Boutonniere Deformities. Clin Plastic Surg 2019; 46:329\u201337. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31103077/","Pfanner S, Poggetti A. Swan-Neck and Boutonniere Deformity in Rheumatoid Hand. Hand Clin. 2025;41(1):103-116. doi:10.1016/j.hcl.2024.08.004"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85194"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13850"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20797"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20797","links":{"self":"ht